## Architecture Review — 2026-03-16 Complete

**Codebase health: On track.** Zero build errors, zero Clippy warnings, all tests pass.

---

### Security Posture

Three exploitable issues found, all introduced by Claude:

| ID | P | Finding |
|----|---|---------|
| red-cell-c2-5ujg | **P1** | `OperatorConfig` derives `Debug` — plaintext passwords in any debug log |
| red-cell-c2-bdnw | **P2** | `AgentRecord` serializes AES key/IV — one wrong REST route exposes all session keys |
| red-cell-c2-yz7q | **P2** | Discord webhook URL not validated as HTTPS — teamserver becomes an SSRF proxy |
| red-cell-c2-4rsi | **P2** | `agent_id=0` accepted in DEMON_INIT — sentinel ID not rejected |
| red-cell-c2-5a1q | **P2** | DNS upload has no per-IP session cap — unauthenticated upload buffer saturation |
| red-cell-c2-lbxd | **P3** | Download/socket errors silently discarded in dispatch |
| red-cell-c2-wg35 | **P3** | `Mutex::unwrap()` in test-only Argon2 cache — cascades under poison |
| red-cell-c2-mk68 | **P3** | No test for `agent_id=0` rejection |

---

### Biggest Blindspot

**`AgentRecord` is fully serializable including AES-256 session keys.** The `Serialize` derive has no `#[serde(skip)]` on the `encryption` field. Today it's safe only by convention — all routes happen to use the `AgentInfo` projection. One future route mistake exposes every registered agent's session key.

---

### Agent Quality

Claude is writing the best code by a clear margin. The auth hardening (Argon2, constant-time comparisons, dummy verifier, rate limiters) is well-reasoned. All findings are latent risks, not live bugs.

### Priority Actions

1. Commit the already-in-progress `OperatorConfig` Debug fix (P1, in working tree)
2. Add `#[serde(skip)]` on `AgentRecord::encryption` (P2)
3. Require `https://` for webhook URLs in `Profile::validate()` (P2)
4. Reject `agent_id=0` in `parse_at_for_listener` (P2)
5. Add per-IP DNS upload session cap (P2)
